y (expect error), column index out of bounds, and different match flags.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Test requires actual cells forming the lookup table and range resolution.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.18,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The IF function correctly handles nested conditions","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Testing IF logic with hardcoded condition values can catch some bugs, but the example formula =IF(A1>10, IF(A1>20, \"high\", \"medium\"), \"low\") requires resolving cell reference A1 and passing its value to the condition evaluator. Mocking A1 hides bugs in type coercion (string vs. number comparison) or issues in how cell values are resolved.","test_description":"Create cell A1 and test with values 5, 15, 25 separately. For each, create formula =IF(A1>10, IF(A1>20, \"high\", \"medium\"), \"low\") and verify results are \"low\", \"medium\", \"high\" respectively. Test with boolean, text, and edge-case values to catch type coercion bugs.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Test requires cell references and proper type casting in condition evaluation.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.12,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"CONCATENATE joins cell values with the correct separator and handles empty cells by skipping them rather than inserting blank strings","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"While CONCATENATE logic with hardcoded empty strings can be unit-tested, the issue is specifically about how empty CELLS are handled in the spreadsheet context. A real failure is when the engine represents an empty cell (no value) incorrectly to CONCATENATE, leading to wrong output. Integration testing with actual empty cells ensures the engine correctly represents empty-cell semantics.","test_description":"Create cells A1=\"hello\", B1=(empty), C1=\"world\", and formula =CONCATENATE(